  RELEVANCE: Exemplifies position that democratic traditions (competitive elections, parliamentary debate) provide legitimacy without requiring entrenched written constitutional traditions enforced by judges. Challenges dominant view that constitutional traditions require judicial guardianship. Essential for project's question of when inherited traditions support versus constrain democratic values—Bellamy argues democratic traditions are self-correcting and don't need extra-democratic constitutional constraints. Shows republican political tradition offers alternative to liberal constitutionalism.

