  RELEVANCE: Advances debate on how constitutional traditions can remain legitimate across time and reasonable disagreement. Shows tensions in grounding legitimacy in inherited constitutional traditions when citizens reasonably disagree not just about comprehensive doctrines but about political principles themselves. Crucial for project's examination of tradition's value—demonstrates that tradition-based legitimacy becomes unstable when the traditions themselves (liberal constitutionalism) fracture into competing interpretations. Raises question whether constitutional traditions can sustain legitimacy amid deepening pluralism.

