  pages = {1419--1431},
  doi = {10.1177/01914537241293372},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Political liberalism's legitimacy conception requires reconciling democratic popular sovereignty with constraints imposed by inherited constitutional regimes. Drawing on H.L.A. Hart's internal/external perspective distinction, argues that citizens must simultaneously adopt internal attitude of bonding to their society's ongoing legal project and external attitude of critical judgment about whether that project is reasonably acceptable. Constitutional traditions gain legitimacy not merely through past constituent power but through this dual perspective—living within tradition while critically evaluating its justifiability to free and equal citizens.

  RELEVANCE: Addresses fundamental tension in tradition-based constitutional legitimacy: how can inherited constitutional constraints be democratically legitimate if current citizens had no say in their creation? Michelman's solution—combining internal commitment to legal tradition with external critical evaluation—provides sophisticated answer to project's question of when traditions are valuable. Shows legitimacy of constitutional traditions depends on citizens' reflective equilibrium between acceptance of inherited framework and reasoned judgment of its justifiability. Essential for understanding democratic value of legal-constitutional traditions.

