  year = {2008},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Democracy's authority derives from epistemic proceduralism—democratic procedures are legitimate because they tend to produce correct or better political decisions than alternative methods while being acceptable to all qualified points of view. Democracy combines epistemic value (truth-tracking) with procedural fairness. Democratic traditions and institutions have authority not merely from agreement or fairness but because they are reasonably regarded as epistemically superior to alternatives (rule by experts, monarchy, etc.) in conditions of reasonable disagreement about who the experts are.

  RELEVANCE: Provides epistemic justification for democratic traditions' value—they track political truth better than alternatives while remaining publicly justifiable. Important for project because it shows democratic traditions aren't merely stable compromises but have cognitive virtues. Addresses question of why specifically democratic traditions matter by arguing they balance epistemic reliability with legitimacy constraints. Shows tension between tradition (inherited procedures) and epistemic responsiveness (updating procedures when better alternatives emerge).

