  year = {2017},
  volume = {39},
  number = {2},
  pages = {295--324},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Weber's conception of legitimacy as belief in legitimacy (legitimacy beliefs) is more useful for political theory than moralized liberal conceptions. Political legitimacy should be understood sociologically as stable acceptance of authority by subjects, not as moral justification meeting liberal standards. Traditional legitimacy—authority accepted because "it has always been this way"—is genuine form of political legitimacy, not mere stability. Liberal philosophers wrongly dismiss Weberian legitimacy as merely descriptive; legitimacy beliefs themselves have normative significance for political order.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges liberal assumption that traditions need moral justification to confer legitimacy. Provides alternative conception where traditional authority is legitimate simply through stable acceptance, not through meeting reasonability standards. Important for project because it takes seriously the legitimating power of tradition as such, not tradition-as-justified. Raises question whether traditions' value lies in their stability-producing function rather than their justifiability. Shows tension between liberal emphasis on reflective endorsement and conservative/Weberian emphasis on unreflective acceptance of inherited authority.

