  year = {2019},
  volume = {20},
  pages = {398--420},
  doi = {10.1177/1474885118806677},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Harrington's republicanism grounds legitimacy in dual requirements: popular power (broad property distribution enabling political participation) and aristocratic authority (auctoritas). Republican legitimacy requires both democratic liberty through property and integration of authority as traditional respect for wisdom and virtue. Liberty alone is insufficient; legitimate republics need hierarchical authority tradition (auctoritas) binding popular power. This dual theory distinguishes Harrington's republicanism from both Hobbesian liberalism and pure democratic populism.

  RELEVANCE: Shows how republican tradition reconciles democratic equality with hierarchical authority traditions. Important for project's question of when traditions are valuable—Harrington argues legitimate polities need both egalitarian traditions (property-based citizenship) and hierarchical traditions (auctoritas, deference to wisdom). Demonstrates that even within republican-democratic theory, certain aristocratic/traditional elements are considered essential for legitimacy. Raises question whether democratic traditions alone suffice or whether they require supplementation by traditions of deference, expertise, or authority.

